body:
I am designing a CPU which needs the memory to be byte addressable but has 4-byte wide addressing (risc-v). To ensure it gets synthesized to BRAM, I've created 4 separate 1 byte-wide rams which are managed by a memory controller.

However, if I want to access unaligned memory i.e. not multiples of 4, I need to permute the values I read from the memory modules accordingly.

This has the side effect of the read data depending directly on the address in a combinational block thus causing `UNOPTFLAT`.

I've encountered this issue many times and most times I could split my code to be in a different `always` block and that fixed it. However, here I have a `case` statement which I can't split out.

Here is the code which is causing the problem:

```verilog
assign offset = a[1:0];
assign a_by_4 = a >> 2;
assign a_plus_1 = a_by_4 + 1;

always_comb begin
  case(offset)
    2'd0: begin
      a0 = a_by_4;
      a1 = a_by_4;
      a2 = a_by_4;
      a3 = a_by_4;
    end
    2'd1: begin
      a0 = a_plus_1;
      a1 = a_by_4;
      a2 = a_by_4;
      a3 = a_by_4;
    end
    2'd2: begin
      a0 = a_plus_1;
      a1 = a_plus_1;
      a2 = a_by_4;
      a3 = a_by_4;
    end
    2'd3: begin
      a0 = a_plus_1;
      a1 = a_plus_1;
      a2 = a_plus_1;
      a3 = a_by_4;
    end
  endcase
end

always_comb begin
  case(offset)
    2'd0: rd = {rd3, rd2, rd1, rd0};
    2'd1: rd = {rd0, rd3, rd2, rd1};
    2'd2: rd = {rd1, rd0, rd3, rd2};
    2'd3: rd = {rd2, rd1, rd0, rd3};
  endcase
end
```
The error message is quite clear and I understand the problem:

```bash
verilator -Wall -cc -build --trace rtl/top.sv -Irtl
%Warning-UNOPTFLAT: rtl/top.sv:42:15: Signal unoptimizable: Feedback to clock or circular logic: 'top.mem_adr'
   42 | logic [31:0]  mem_adr;
      |               ^~~~~~~
                    ... For warning description see https://verilator.org/warn/UNOPTFLAT?v=4.215
                    ... Use "/* verilator lint_off UNOPTFLAT */" and lint_on around source to disable this message.
                    rtl/top.sv:42:15:      Example path: top.mem_adr
                    rtl/mem_controller.sv:78:1:      Example path: ALWAYS
                    rtl/top.sv:30:15:      Example path: top.mem_rd
                    rtl/mux2.sv:8:12:      Example path: ASSIGNW
                    rtl/top.sv:29:15:      Example path: top.inst
                    rtl/control.sv:128:1:      Example path: ALWAYS
                    rtl/top.sv:18:15:      Example path: top.c_adrsrc
                    rtl/mux2.sv:8:12:      Example path: ASSIGNW
                    rtl/top.sv:42:15:      Example path: top.mem_adr
%Error: Exiting due to 1 warning(s)
make: *** [Makefile:31: top] Error 1

```

Unfortunately, I don't know how to fix it. Steps that I tried:

 1. Follow along and split various signals into separate `always` blocks. Keep doing this and I end up at another place where I have a similar case like the above.
 2. Tried the comment `split_var` on all the signals in the generated by `--report-unoptflat`. That didn't work either.
 3. As a last option, tried `lint_off` for unoptflat. That worked fine for aligned memory access but threw `DIDNOTCONVERGE` error for unaligned access.

In the code above, if I remove the dependency on `offset`, the error goes away i.e. :

```verilog
always_comb begin
  rd = {rd3, rd2, rd1, rd0};
end
```

Any suggestions on how I can fix this? I can't think of any way to remove the dependency of `rd` on `offset`. If there isn't a way, I might need to either try a completely different approach for memory or drop unaligned access completely.

Thanks in advance!
